¥section*{8. Exponential function}

Given
¥[
f(x)=k^3(k^x)+b,¥qquad x¥ge 0,
¥]
where $k$ and $b$ are positive constants and $k<1$.

This simplifies to
¥[
f(x)=k^{x+3}+b.
¥]

¥textbf{I.} The maximum value is displayed as a constant or coefficient.

Since $0<k<1$, $k^{x+3}$ decreases as $x$ increases. The maximum occurs at $x=0$:
¥[
f(0)=k^3+b.
¥]
This is not shown as a single constant or coefficient in the function. So I is false.

¥textbf{II.} $f(1)=f(0)¥cdot k$

Compute:
¥[
f(1)=k^4+b
¥]
while
¥[
f(0)¥cdot k=(k^3+b)k=k^4+bk.
¥]
These are not always equal. So II is false.

¥textbf{III.} $f(a)<b$ for some $a>0$

But
¥[
f(a)=k^{a+3}+b.
¥]
Since $k^{a+3}>0$,
¥[
f(a)>b
¥]
for all $a>0$. So III is false.

Therefore none of I, II, III must be true.

¥[
¥boxed{¥text{D}}
¥]

¥section*{9. Maximum value of $k$}

Given
¥[
15x^{18}+kx^9+24
¥]
has factors
¥[
ax^9+b ¥quad ¥text{and} ¥quad cx^9+d,
¥]
with integers $a,b,c,d$.

Let
¥[
y=x^9.
¥]
Then
¥[
15y^2+ky+24=(ay+b)(cy+d).
¥]

Expanding:
¥[
(ay+b)(cy+d)=acy^2+(ad+bc)y+bd.
¥]
So
¥[
ac=15,¥qquad bd=24,¥qquad k=ad+bc.
¥]

To maximize $k$, choose factor pairs to make $ad+bc$ as large as possible.

Take
¥[
a=15,¥ c=1,¥ b=1,¥ d=24.
¥]
Then
¥[
k=ad+bc=15(24)+1(1)=360+1=361.
¥]

Thus the maximum value is
¥[
¥boxed{361}.
¥]

¥section*{10. Factored quadratic expression}

Given
¥[
(hx+k)(qx+z)=ax^2+bx+35
¥]
with integers $h,k,q,z$.

Expanding:
¥[
(hx+k)(qx+z)=hqx^2+(hz+kq)x+kz.
¥]
Therefore
¥[
a=hq,¥qquad b=hz+kq,¥qquad kz=35.
¥]

¥textbf{I.} $¥dfrac{35}{k}$

Since $kz=35$ and $k,z$ are integers,
¥[
¥frac{35}{k}=z,
¥]
which is an integer. So I is true.

¥textbf{II.} $b$

Since
¥[
b=hz+kq,
¥]
and all variables are integers, $b$ must be an integer. So II is true.

¥textbf{III.} $-¥dfrac{a}{q}$

Since
¥[
a=hq,
¥]
then
¥[
-¥frac{a}{q}=-¥frac{hq}{q}=-h,
¥]
which is an integer. So III is true.

¥[
¥boxed{¥text{D}}
¥]

¥section*{11. Quadratic with equal outputs}

Given
¥[
f(x)=-3x^2+bx+c.
¥]

Also
¥[
f(-4)=f(8).
¥]
Since a parabola is symmetric about its axis, the axis is the midpoint of $-4$ and $8$:
¥[
x=¥frac{-4+8}{2}=2.
¥]

For
¥[
f(x)=ax^2+bx+c,
¥]
the axis is
¥[
x=-¥frac{b}{2a}.
¥]
Here $a=-3$, so
¥[
x=-¥frac{b}{2(-3)}=¥frac{b}{6}.
¥]
Thus
¥[
¥frac{b}{6}=2 ¥Rightarrow b=12.
¥]

¥textbf{I.} $r+s=4$

The sum of the roots is
¥[
-¥frac{b}{a}=-¥frac{12}{-3}=4.
¥]
So I is true.

¥textbf{II.} $b<0$

But $b=12>0$, so II is false.

¥textbf{III.} $c<k$

Since the parabola opens downward, the vertex gives the maximum value. Since the axis is at $x=2$, the vertex is not at $x=0$, so
¥[
f(2)=k>f(0)=c.
¥]
Thus
¥[
c<k.
¥]
III is true.

So I and III only.

¥[
¥boxed{¥text{C}}
¥]

¥section*{12. Rock height model}

The rock reaches its maximum height of $200$ feet at $t=3$, and hits the ground at $t=8$.

Since the axis of symmetry is at $t=3$, and one root is at $t=8$, the other root must be at
¥[
t=3-(8-3)= -2.
¥]

So the quadratic can be written as
¥[
h(t)=a(t+2)(t-8).
¥]

Use the maximum point $(3,200)$:
¥[
200=a(3+2)(3-8)=a(5)(-5)=-25a.
¥]
Thus
¥[
a=-8.
¥]

Now find the initial height:
¥[
c=h(0)=-8(0+2)(0-8)=-8(2)(-8)=128.
¥]

¥[
¥boxed{128}
¥]

¥section*{13. Quadratic with one real solution}

Given
¥[
2rx^2-5sx+8r=0
¥]
has one real solution and
¥[
rs=160.
¥]

For one real solution, the discriminant is zero:
¥[
(-5s)^2-4(2r)(8r)=0.
¥]
So
¥[
25s^2-64r^2=0
¥]
and
¥[
25s^2=64r^2.
¥]
Thus
¥[
5|s|=8|r|.
¥]

This suggests
¥[
|r|=10,¥qquad |s|=16
¥]
because
¥[
5(16)=8(10)=80
¥]
and
¥[
|rs|=10¥cdot 16=160.
¥]

Since $rs=160>0$, $r$ and $s$ have the same sign, so
¥[
|r+s|=|10+16|=26.
¥]

¥[
¥boxed{26}
¥]

¥section*{14. Polynomial sign analysis}

Given
¥[
f(x)=-(x+a)^2(x-b)(x-c),
¥]
where $a,b,c$ are positive constants and
¥[
b<k<c.
¥]

¥textbf{I.} $k>0$

Since $b>0$ and $k>b$, we must have
¥[
k>0.
¥]
So I is true.

¥textbf{II.} $f(k)>0$

Evaluate the signs:
¥[
(k+a)^2>0,
¥]
¥[
k-b>0,
¥]
¥[
k-c<0.
¥]
So
¥[
(x-b)(x-c)¥Big|_{x=k}=(k-b)(k-c)<0.
¥]
Then
¥[
-(k+a)^2(k-b)(k-c)>0.
¥]
So II is true.

¥textbf{III.} $f(0)>0$

Compute:
¥[
f(0)=-(a)^2(-b)(-c).
¥]
Since $(-b)(-c)=bc>0$, we get
¥[
f(0)=-a^2bc<0.
¥]
So III is false.

Therefore I and II only.

¥[
¥boxed{¥text{A}}
¥]

