¥section*{17. Right triangle statements}

In $¥triangle ABC$, $¥angle B=90^¥circ$, $AB=12$, and $D$ lies on segment $AC$.

¥textbf{I.} $BC=12¥tan(¥angle CAB)$

By definition,
¥[
¥tan(¥angle CAB)=¥frac{BC}{AB}=¥frac{BC}{12}.
¥]
Thus
¥[
BC=12¥tan(¥angle CAB).
¥]
So I is true.

¥textbf{II.} $¥cos(¥angle ABD)-¥sin(¥angle DBC)=0$

Since $D$ lies on $AC$, ray $BD$ splits the right angle at $B$:
¥[
¥angle ABD+¥angle DBC=90^¥circ.
¥]
Therefore the two angles are complementary, so
¥[
¥cos(¥angle ABD)=¥sin(¥angle DBC).
¥]
Hence
¥[
¥cos(¥angle ABD)-¥sin(¥angle DBC)=0.
¥]
So II is true.

¥textbf{III.} $¥angle ABD=¥angle BDC$

This is not always true just because $D$ is on $AC$. There is not enough information.

So I and II only.

¥[
¥boxed{¥text{A}}
¥]

¥section*{18. Altitude in right triangle}

In $¥triangle ABC$, $¥angle B=90^¥circ$, $BD$ is an altitude to hypotenuse $AC$, $BC=10$, and
¥[
¥angle ABD=60^¥circ.
¥]

Since $BD¥perp AC$, triangle $ABD$ is a right triangle with $¥angle ADB=90^¥circ$. Therefore
¥[
¥angle BAD=30^¥circ.
¥]

Because $¥angle BAD=¥angle A$ in the large triangle, $¥triangle ABC$ is a $30^¥circ$-$60^¥circ$-$90^¥circ$ triangle. Side $BC$ is opposite $30^¥circ$, so it is the short leg:
¥[
BC=10.
¥]
Thus the hypotenuse is
¥[
AC=20,
¥]
and the other leg is
¥[
AB=10¥sqrt3.
¥]

Using the right triangle altitude relationship,
¥[
AD=¥frac{AB^2}{AC}.
¥]
So
¥[
AD=¥frac{(10¥sqrt3)^2}{20}=¥frac{300}{20}=15.
¥]

¥[
¥boxed{15}
¥]

